Subject: [PATCH 0/9] futex: PID namespace agnostic robust futexes via owner cookies

Robust futexes identify the lock owner by storing the owner's TID in the
futex word and comparing it against the exiting task's TID during the
robust list exit walk. TIDs are only unique within a PID namespace, so
this identification is ambiguous for futexes in memory shared across PID
namespaces: a task dying in one namespace can be misidentified as the
owner of a lock legitimately held by a live task in another namespace,
which corrupts the lock word (FUTEX_OWNER_DIED gets set, the owner field
cleared, a waiter woken) and breaks mutual exclusion. This has been a
known limitation of robust futexes ever since PID namespaces were
introduced.

Patches 1 and 2 stand apart from the rest: they fix a lost wakeup
window which exists in the classic TID based robust futex protocol
today, independent of anything else in this series. A robust unlock
wipes FUTEX_WAITERS along with the owner TID and wakes a single
waiter; if that waiter is killed before it can act on the wakeup and
the futex was re-acquired through the uncontended fast path in the
meantime, the dying waiter's exit walk discards its pending op (owner
mismatch) without waking anybody, and the remaining waiters sleep
forever behind an owner which will never see contention. The fix
replays the possibly consumed wakeup unconditionally: the ABI only
obliges waiters to arm FUTEX_WAITERS before sleeping, so an observed
bit carries no owner side wakeup promise the kernel could rely on,
and a spurious wakeup is harmless (patch 4 adds an opt-in for
protocols which do provide the owner side guarantee). Deterministic
selftests pin down the semantics, and deterministic, racing and stock
glibc (pthread_mutex_t with PTHREAD_MUTEX_ROBUST and
PTHREAD_PROCESS_SHARED, nothing else) reproducers demonstrate the
hang on current kernels - the racing ones strand a waiter within a
handful of kill rounds on a stock 6.8 host. The window was found by model
checking the wait/wake interactions (see below). These two patches can
be taken separately if preferred.

The rest of the series makes the owner identifier user space policy:

Patch 3 extends sys_set_robust_list() with an extensible list head
(struct robust_list_head2, selected by size, carrying a validated flags
word). With ROBUST_LIST_COOKIE set, the exit walk compares the futex
word against a user space managed 32-bit cookie instead of the TID: for
queued entries a cookie stored at cookie_offset relative to the entry
(written only by the lock owner), for the pending operation the task
private list_op_pending_cookie. The exit walk handles the pending
operation before the queued entries, since a queued entry can be the
lease which keeps the pending cookie allocated. This alone suffices for
robust mutexes whose users can assign unique cookies out of band, e.g.
via allocation tables in the shared memory itself (ordered after all
held locks in the list) or via OFD file locks, both of which release
the identifier no earlier than the holder's exit cleanup.

Patch 4 adds ROBUST_LIST_WAITERS_STRICT, a second flag for the
extensible list head (independent of ROBUST_LIST_COOKIE): a protocol
whose lock owners guarantee that FUTEX_WAITERS is only ever cleared
by an unlock which issues a wakeup - glibc's mutexes qualify - can
declare that discipline, and the exit walk then suppresses the
consumed-wakeup replay of patch 1 whenever the futex value carries
the bit, since the bit already guarantees a wakeup from the live
owner. Classic robust_list_head users keep the unconditional replay.

For POSIX style process shared mutexes, which have no natural home for
an allocation protocol, a per lock reservation counter can provide the
cookies: every lock attempt draws a fresh 30-bit value. Finite counters
wrap, so the protocol must guarantee that a stale reservation (drawn a
full counter period ago) can never be published into the lock word, and
that a dead task's robust list state is never interpreted against a
lock whose (wrapped) cookie happens to match numerically. Patches 6-8
provide the required kernel assists:

Patch 6 adds __vdso_futex_robust_list{64,32}_cmpxchg_rseq(): the lock
side counterpart of __vdso_futex_robust_list{64,32}_try_unlock(). It
validates that TLS::rseq::rseq_cs is still armed (the caller arms it
before drawing the reservation, so any RSEQ event in between
invalidates the attempt), arms list_op_pending and performs the
cmpxchg. The window between the check and the cmpxchg is made atomic
against RSEQ events by a kernel fixup, and the pending op disarm on
failure is atomic against signal delivery like in the try_unlock
functions. The patch also adds exit time fixups which disarm a pending
op that a fatal-signal death left behind in a state where processing it
would be invalid (uncommitted lock attempt, completed unlock). Both
exit time fixup windows were found by model checking, see below.

Patch 8 adds MEMBARRIER_CMD_SHARED_EXPEDITED_RSEQ, an RSEQ fence
covering every process which has a shared writable mapping of the page
containing a given address and has registered with the accompanying
registration command. This is the quiescence operation executed on
counter epoch changes: it guarantees that no reservation drawn before
the epoch change can pass the rseq_cs validation afterwards. The
address is passed via a new fourth syscall argument, following the
precedent of the cpu_id argument added in 2a36ab717e8f
("rseq/membarrier: Add MEMBARRIER_CMD_PRIVATE_EXPEDITED_RSEQ").

Patches 2, 5, 7 and 9 add selftests, including a reproducer of the
original cross-namespace corruption (two processes in different PID
namespaces observing the same namespace local TID) which demonstrates
that the cookie variant leaves the foreign-owned lock alone.

The protocols were modeled in TLA+ (explicit cookie assignment and the
full counter/reservation/fence protocol, including death at arbitrary
points, delayed exit cleanup, futex waiters with adversarial wake
selection, and counter wraparound with a miniature cookie space). TLC
validates the final design (safety, lock recovery and no-lost-wakeup
liveness) and demonstrably has teeth: it finds the classic TID
collision corruption, the corruption resulting from attributing the
pending op through the shared entry cookie (which is why
list_op_pending_cookie exists), the robustness loss of that variant
even with exit fixups in place, the two exit time fixup windows of
patch 6 - one of which (death between a committed vdso unlock and the
pending op disarm, processed after the lock was re-acquired under a
wrapped cookie) was a genuine model checker counterexample against a
design believed correct at the time - and the lost wakeup window fixed
by patch 1, which turned out not to be cookie specific at all (both
the unconditional replay and its ROBUST_LIST_WAITERS_STRICT
suppression pass the no-lost-wakeup liveness exhaustively).
Reference user space implementations of all three cookie assignment
schemes, benchmarks against pthread mutexes and the TLA+ specifications
are available and can be posted alongside if desired.

All patches survive the futex and membarrier selftests plus
multi-process / cross PID namespace kill stress tests of the reference
mutex implementations under QEMU. The kernel patches build and work
standalone at each point of the series for bisectability.

Note on checkpatch: the remaining errors are parser artifacts (an asm
label colon inside a stringified macro, matching the existing LABEL()
macro in vfutex.c, and _Atomic()/function pointer declarations in the
selftests, matching the existing code in robust_list.c).

